{"author":{"id":"1949ffc23f11a8cb4f8c42a45c9ad241b49570df9a18687489e9ea78d87c54a3"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1771944047,"nonce":"vebb6Or2hTc/2olQHyUCOuis5T0=","title":"Design: RL training components vs graph components — UI integration and user experience","message":"## Problem\n\nfeedbax has two execution pathways:\n\n1. **Graph pipeline** — Components connected by Wires, topologically sorted execution, supports backprop for optimal control. Visible in the graph editor UI.\n\n2. **RL pipeline** — Functional env step/reset, PPO/SAC training loop, rollout collection. Currently separate from the graph system (env.py, ppo.py). Not visible in the graph editor.\n\nThis creates a potential UX problem: some training elements (observation normalization, reward shaping, curriculum) exist in a liminal space between \"part of the dynamical system\" and \"part of the training procedure.\" Users switching between OC and RL training modes may not get clear cues about which elements are available, active, or relevant.\n\n## Design Questions\n\n1. **What belongs in the graph vs training config?**\n   - The dynamical system (plant, controller, sensors, task) → graph\n   - Training hyperparameters (learning rate, batch size, algorithm) → training tab\n   - Observation normalization: graph node AND/OR training config?\n   - Reward function: graph component? training config? both?\n   - Curriculum: purely training config\n\n2. **Mode switching UX**: When a user switches from OC to RL training:\n   - The graph (the system) stays the same\n   - The training tab changes from \"optimizer: L-BFGS, loss: cost function\" to \"algorithm: PPO, rollout: 256 steps\"\n   - Should RL-only elements (e.g., discrete reward function node) be grayed out in OC mode?\n   - Should OC-only elements (e.g., differentiable cost node) be grayed out in RL mode?\n\n3. **Common operations as modifiers vs graph nodes**: Some operations are so common (normalization, noise injection, gain) that forcing them to be explicit graph nodes may be cumbersome. Should feedbax support \"modifiers\" — transformations attached to existing nodes that appear as badges/overlays in the UI rather than separate nodes? This would let users apply normalization to a network's input without manually wiring a separate normalizer node.\n\n4. **Automatic inference**: When a modifier (e.g., normalizer) is attached to a node, can feedbax infer which variables need normalization based on the actual input ports/wires? The full state gets passed everywhere, but port connections reveal which subset is actually used.\n\n## Considerations\n\n- The graph is the canonical representation of the system. Training is meta to it.\n- Users should never be confused about \"is this element active in my current training mode?\"\n- The distinction matters for correctness: backprop requires differentiable graphs; RL treats the system as a black box.\n- Some elements genuinely serve both modes (e.g., a signal-processing node like Gain).\n- This is a design/architecture issue, not an implementation task. Needs careful thought before building.\n\n## References\n\n- Codex recommended Option A (standalone Component) for observation normalization, which fits the graph pipeline but leaves the RL pipeline question open.\n- The RL policy (ActorCritic in policy.py) is a plain eqx.Module, NOT a graph Component. This is intentional — the policy doesn't need graph composition — but it means normalization for RL must be handled at the PPO loop level, not through graph wiring.","files":null}]}